Ethical AI Use in Healthcare
“Ensuring Responsible AI Deployment in Healthcare”

1. Patient Consent Protocols

All AI systems handling patient data must obtain explicit, informed consent before data collection and use.

Consent forms should be written in clear, accessible language explaining what data is collected, how it will be used, and any associated risks.

Patients must have the right to opt out or withdraw consent at any time without affecting their access to medical services.

2. Bias Mitigation Strategies

Datasets must be audited regularly for demographic imbalances that could lead to biased predictions (e.g., race, gender, age).

Use bias detection tools (e.g., AI Fairness 360) to measure disparate impact, false positive/negative rates, and other fairness metrics.

Retrain models with diverse, representative data and apply de-biasing algorithms where necessary.

3. Transparency Requirements

Make AI system decision-making processes explainable to medical staff and patients. Use interpretable models or post-hoc explanations to clarify outcomes.

Maintain clear documentation on how AI models were developed, including data sources, training methods, and known limitations.

Establish audit trails for AI-assisted diagnoses and treatment recommendations to ensure accountability.

Conclusion:
Implementing these protocols fosters trust, protects patient rights, and minimizes harm. Responsible AI in healthcare should prioritize fairness, accountability, and patient well-being.

